[If one looks at the report above, one sees we are now up to 14 countries that have reported polio isolates in the past 12 months either from individuals with AFP (acute flaccid paralysis), asymptomatic contacts of AFP cases, or "just" environmental samples. A 15th country had reported a poliovirus type 2 isolate a short while back -- Central African Republic -- but further information on that isolate has not been available.

There are now 3 countries that have recently confirmed WPV1 isolates -- Afghanistan and Pakistan continue to have cases (and in addition to the 2 cases in Pakistan we reported from a media report yesterday, 20 Jun 2019, a 3rd case was reported in a media report plus on the End Polio Pakistan website today, 21 Jun 2019). Iran has reported a 3rd isolate, again in Sistan and Balochistan province, again genetically related to WPV1 circulating in Sindh province, Pakistan and again just in an environmental sample. Hence, the WPV1 continues to circulate in Iran, luckily thus far not associated with AFP disease in any of the population in Iran.

As for the countries with cVDPVs, there appear to be 3 main exporters of cVDPVs in Africa -- Nigeria (from the Jigawa associated outbreak), Somalia, and the DR Congo (Democratic Republic of the Congo). Is this the polioviruses' last hurrah before transmission is interrupted? Or is this our future continually close to interruption of transmission and recurrent hiccups?

