[2] Pakistan (Khyber Pakhtunkhwa): media report
Date: Fri 21 Jun 2019
Source: The News International (Pakistan) [edited]
https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/487692-three-more-children-diagnosed-with-polio-in-kp


Polio continued to hit children in the country as 3 more children were diagnosed with the virus on [Thu 20 Jun 2019]. All 3 polio cases were reported from Khyber Pakhtunkhwa. And with the latest 3 cases, the total number of polio cases reached 27 in Pakistan in 2019.

Among the 3 children, a 21-month-old girl, resident of Saidgai village, Takhti Khel Union Council [Bannu district], was diagnosed with polio. She reportedly didn't get any polio vaccine. The child belongs to a poor family and her father is stated to be a driver.

The 2nd polio case was reported from remote mountainous Torghar district, [in] a 10-month-old boy, resident of Gigani, Hernail union council of Judbah subdivision. This child is also stated to have received no dose.

The 3rd polio case was reported from Lakki Marwat [in] a 15-month-old boy, resident of Jadid Mamakhel, Mamakhel union council of Sarae Naurang subdivision. According to the officials, the child belongs to a poor family and his father is a labourer. The area borders the Ghoriwala Union Council of the Bannu district that has become a headache for the government in terms of growing polio cases and challenges on ground.

Out of 27 cases in the country, Punjab and Sindh reported 3 each polio cases and Khyber Pakhtunkhwa has reported 13 [14?] cases so far. In KP, Bannu is on top with 9 cases, followed by North Waziristan [in KPTD] with 5 cases, while Lakki Marwat, Torghar, Hangu, Dera Ismail Khan, Shangla, and Khyber reported 1 polio case each this year [2019].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This media report and the End Polio Pakistan website (see http://www.endpolio.com.pk/polioin-pakistan/polio-cases-district-wise-2019) mention 3 newly confirmed cases reported yesterday (20 Jun 2019). I suspect the case from Torghar district had not been released prior to the publication of the cases from Bannu and Lakki Marwat. It does explain the media report in yesterday's (20 Jun 2019) update dealing with results of a Jirga (tribal council) supporting the polio vaccination activities in Torghar. The addition of these cases brings the number of confirmed cases of WPV1 associated paralytic polio in Pakistan this year (2019) to date to 27, and including yesterday's report of another case in Afghanistan, the global total of WPV1 associated cases to 36, surpassing 2018's full year total of 33 cases.

